T1  - Trading patterns, bid-ask spreads, and estimated security returns: The case of common stocks at calendar turning points
AU  - Keim, Donald B.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 25
IS  - 1
SP  - 75
EP  - 97
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/11/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(89)90097-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X89900974
AB  - Returns computed with closing bid or ask prices that may not represent ‘true’ prices introduce measurement error into portfolio returns if investor buying and selling display systematic patterns. This paper finds systematic tendencies for closing prices to be recorded at the bid in December and at the ask in early January. After changing bid and ask prices are controlled for. this pattern results in large portfolio returns on the two trading days surrounding the end of the year, especially for low-price stocks. Other temporal return patterns (e.g. weekend and holiday effects) are also related to systematic trading patterns.
ER  - 

